name: HashMap
comment:
A hash-table based implementation of dart-core.Map.

The keys of a HashMap must have consistent Object.operator== and dart-core.Object.hashCode implementations. This means that the == operator must define a stable equivalence relation on the keys (reflexive, anti-symmetric, transitive, and consistent over time), and that hashCode must be the same for objects that are considered equal by ==.

The map allows null as a key.

Iterating the map's keys, values or entries (through forEach) may happen in any order. The itearation order only changes when the map is modified. Values are iterated in the same order as their associated keys, so iterating the keys and values in parallel will give matching key and value pairs.

constructors.comment:
Creates an unordered hash-table based dart-core.Map.

The created map is not ordered in any way. When iterating the keys or values, the iteration order is unspecified except that it will stay the same as long as the map isn't changed.

If dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.equals is provided, it is used to compare the keys in the table with new keys. If dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.equals is omitted, the key's own Object.operator== is used instead.

Similar, if dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.hashCode is provided, it is used to produce a hash value for keys in order to place them in the hash table. If it is omitted, the key's own dart-collection.HashMap.hashCode is used.

If using methods like operator, remove and containsKey together with a custom equality and hashcode, an extra isValidKey function can be supplied. This function is called before calling dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.equals or dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.hashCode with an argument that may not be a dart-collection.HashMap.K instance, and if the call returns false, the key is assumed to not be in the set. The dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.isValidKey function defaults to just testing if the object is a dart-collection.HashMap.K instance.

The used equals and hashCode method should always be consistent, so that if equals(a, b) then hashCode(a) == hashCode(b). The hash of an object, or what it compares equal to, should not change while the object is in the table. If it does change, the result is unpredictable.

If you supply one of dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.equals and dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-.hashCode, you should generally also to supply the other. An example would be using dart-core.identical and dart-core.identityHashCode, which is equivalent to using the shorthand dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-identity).

identity.name: identity
identity.comment:
Creates an unordered identity-based map.

Effectively a shorthand for:

new HashMap(equals: identical, hashCode: identityHashCodeOf)

from.name: from
from.comment: Creates a dart-collection.HashMap that contains all key value pairs of dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-from.other.

fromIterable.name: fromIterable
fromIterable.comment:
Creates a dart-collection.HashMap where the keys and values are computed from the dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterable.iterable.

For each element of the dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterable.iterable this constructor computes a key/value pair, by applying dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterable.key and dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterable.value respectively.

The keys of the key/value pairs do not need to be unique. The last occurrence of a key will simply overwrite any previous value.

If no values are specified for dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterable.key and dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterable.value the default is the identity function.

fromIterables.name: fromIterables
fromIterables.comment:
Creates a dart-collection.HashMap associating the given dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.keys to dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.values.

This constructor iterates over dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.keys and dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.values and maps each element of dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.keys to the corresponding element of dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.values.

If dart-collection.HashMap.HashMap-fromIterables.keys contains the same object multiple times, the last occurrence overwrites the previous value.

It is an error if the two dart-core.Iterables don't have the same length.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-collection.HashMap.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

keys.name: keys
keys.comment:
The keys of this.

The returned iterable has efficient length and contains operations, based on dart-collection.HashMap.length and dart-collection.HashMap.containsKey of the map.

The order of iteration is defined by the individual Map implementation, but must be consistent between changes to the map.

values.name: values
values.comment:
The values of this.

The values are iterated in the order of their corresponding keys. This means that iterating dart-collection.HashMap.keys and dart-collection.HashMap.values in parrallel will provided matching pairs of keys and values.

The returned iterable has an efficient length method based on the dart-collection.HashMap.length of the map.

length.name: length
length.comment: The number of key-value pairs in the map.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no key-value pair in the map.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one key-value pair in the map.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-collection.HashMap.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-collection.HashMap.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

[].comment: Returns the value for the given dart-collection.HashMap.[].key or null if dart-collection.HashMap.[].key is not in the map. Because null values are supported, one should either use dart-collection.HashMap.containsKey to distinguish between an absent key and a null value, or use the dart-collection.HashMap.putIfAbsent method.

[]=.comment:
Associates the dart-collection.HashMap.[]=.key with the given dart-collection.HashMap.[]=.value.

If the key was already in the map, its associated value is changed. Otherwise the key-value pair is added to the map.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-collection.HashMap.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-collection.HashMap.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-collection.HashMap.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-collection.HashMap.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

containsValue.name: containsValue
containsValue.comment: Returns true if this map contains the given value.

containsKey.name: containsKey
containsKey.comment: Returns true if this map contains the given key.

putIfAbsent.name: putIfAbsent
putIfAbsent.comment:
If dart-collection.HashMap.putIfAbsent.key is not associated to a value, calls dart-collection.HashMap.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent and updates the map by mapping dart-collection.HashMap.putIfAbsent.key to the value returned by dart-collection.HashMap.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent. Returns the value in the map.

Map<String, int> scores = {'Bob': 36};
for (var key in ['Bob', 'Rohan', 'Sophena']) {
  scores.putIfAbsent(key, () => key.length);
}
scores['Bob'];      // 36
scores['Rohan'];    //  5
scores['Sophena'];  //  7

The code that dart-collection.HashMap.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent executes must not add or remove keys.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Adds all key-value pairs of dart-collection.HashMap.addAll.other to this map.

If a key of dart-collection.HashMap.addAll.other is already in this map, its value is overwritten.

The operation is equivalent to doing this[key] = value for each key and associated value in other. It iterates over dart-collection.HashMap.addAll.other, which must therefore not change during the iteration.

remove.name: remove
remove.comment: Removes the association for the given dart-collection.HashMap.remove.key. Returns the value for dart-collection.HashMap.remove.key in the map or null if dart-collection.HashMap.remove.key is not in the map. Note that values can be null and a returned null value does not always imply that the key is absent.

clear.name: clear
clear.comment:
Removes all pairs from the map.

After this, the map is empty.

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment:
Applies dart-collection.HashMap.forEach.f to each {key, value} pair of the map.

Adding or removing keys from the map during iteration is not allowed.
